	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=28168'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#CC0099;'>Vykadin</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Lorekeeper<br>
			
				Posts: 56<br>
				
				Registered: 04-26-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=28168'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=3#M3">1</a> of 11
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 330 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>Wow, new boards, and I get to be the first post? Lucky me.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I've played a cleric for the last 3-4 years or so, signed up my first account the day that Everquest went live. So I've seen an awful lot of ups and downs in the game. My cleric is my main, and I have always enjoyed playing my cleric the most of all my toons. Frankly, the reason I started him was because I had had such a hard time leveling my monk and wanted a class that would never have a problem finding a group. That proved to be true for much of the last few years. With today's prevalence of cleric bots, however, I find it more and more difficult to find a group. Not impossible, just more difficult. Why should a group invite a cleric as a 6th slot when they have someone who can just sit a cleric outside the group for heals/buffs/rezzes and get a serious DPS class to help up the dps and experience? The prevalence of cleric bots isn't a real reason for "balancing" clerics however, and I've also had groups with a wizard, mage, or any other dps class that was botted outside the group. So what can I say about cleric balancing and our relationship to the other priest classes? I have never played a druid, and have only played a shaman enough to be just dangerous with my knowledge of their spells. I do know the cleric class extremely well though.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Clerics have been called a one trick pony. We can heal, that is our forte. Our nukes? Not even second best. I keep Condemnation loaded only because with elemental glove's 25% reduction in mana requirement it becomes my most mana efficient nuke. With its long cast and recast time I never get a chance to cast it more then once per fight. DoTs? They reside at the back of my spell book. They fizzle more then any other spell I cast, get resisted, and are undead only. Do I cast them? Occasionally. For kicks. But they are so situational as to be almost useless. Much more effective in those rare times that I might cast them to use our undead nukes. But these issues have all been rehashed over and over. I'm supposed to be discussing cleric balancing.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>So what needs to be balanced? Do druids and shamans need more healing? Maybe. I don't really know, nor do I care. Do I mind if they can fill in for a cleric's role better in end game encounters? Not at all. I see druids spot healing in my guild's raids all the time. I have yet to see a druid sit in for a cleric in a CH rotation however. Am I against raising the druids and shaman's healing powers? Not at all, but that would come with a caveat. I may be called selfish, but what do I get out of raising druid/shaman healing? My class lacks utility. Generally. I can't invis. I can't levitate. I can't solo efficiently. Period. I can't quad, or charm for awsome experience. Nor is the cleric class alone in this. Many other classes have no soloing options. Warriors, Rogues and Paladins are stuck with the grouping dilemma as well. So am I asking to be given the ability to solo? Well, it would be nice, but how to do it without stepping on other classes toes or making me some sort of amazing holy warrior? Frankly I don't have any answers to this. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Clerics have a lot of great spells. We have great buffs, great heals, great rezzes. I don't mind that my best buff isn't used in the end game in favor of Symbol and the druids 9 spells. I think its great that the classes working together are more powerful then alone. I don't really even mind the peridot costs these days. I'm long past the ability to spend my platinum on gear upgrades or spells, and HoV only costs me 2 peridots. I do remember a time though when I was constantly pressed for cash and peridot costs were more then I could easily afford. I still feel for the lower level classes and this is definitely something I think should be reconsidered at low levels.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Cleric balance so far has consisted of upgrading our hammers, Yaulp VI, and lowering the cost of casting our little hammer pet. These were a semi decent start, however they did the vast majority of lower level clerics absolutely nothing. No matter what people say, the hammer pet is a joke. It doesn't scale in power with your level. We get the spell at about level 53-54 and it does the same pathetic damage at 65 as it did then. The fact that it is the spell on our ornate pants is, frankly, embarassing. I do use this spell occasionally. I'll haul it out, mem and cast it on various end game boss fights that I know will last 10-20 minutes or so. Usually of course this bites me in the butt because there will be a call to reposition the mob and I can't call off the little bugger. The summoned hammers are fun, and pretty spectacular even against non-undead mobs. Sometimes I feel like I'm holding a machine gun I'll get so many procs in a row. I have become a serious multi tasking battle cleric in a good group. I can stand up behind the mob pounding and proccing away while watching the health of my group mates, switch targets, heal, or divine arbitrate the group to save the day. Follow up with a celestial remedy or group heal, and get back to pounding. With Yaulp VI and a KEI etc. I can even keep up mana wise without having to worry about medding. DPS wise, while fun, I am usually better off sitting my butt down medding, and standing to cast the occasional Condemnation; the procs from the hammer are impressive, but generally at the end of the battle they add up to about what I would have done casting my one allotted nuke per fight.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>So here comes the crux of the issue of priest rebalancing for me. The fear for me is that any increase in the healing power of druids and shaman will render me and my class obsolete. Sure, we have the market cornered on ressurections (not that the druids and shaman are taking that sitting down), but the general fear is that if druids and shaman could heal even 75% as well as clerics then we will never be able to find a group again. No groups mean no experience since we can't solo. Not even against undead. I have read the druid and shaman boards and I understand their frustration at the end game. I'm prepared to give up a little of our healing and maybe even our rezzing to the other priests, but I would hope that in return I get a little flexibility. This isn't about levitation or even an invisibility spell bone thrown to me. So here are my suggestions, and note none of them are original:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1. Plate Mitigation - We are the only priest class that can wear plate armor (shaman wear chain and druids leather) yet we are put on the same plate mitigation table as casters. That means that all that heavy plate we wear might as well be cloth for all the good it does us. Take an enchanter and a cleric with equal AC and we both take the same damage from a hit that lands. We are a plate class, so we should have the benefit of being a plate class. I'm not asking for my dodge skill to be raised or anything like that. I just think that as a plate wearing, mace weilding cleric I should be able to stand there and laugh at the mob a little as they pound on me and I cast my heals. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2. Solo Ability - This is laughable for clerics even versus undead mobs which are few and far between. As stated above, we don't really have plate mitigation, so all that vaunted AC I've been collecting means almost nothing if I try and stand toe to toe and pound it out. So why did I get this Yaulp VI and this summoned hammer if I'm not really supposed to stand up and fight? Root rotting is definitely an option versus some undead. Even with max FT and KEI, however, this isn't efficient. It ends up taking me most of my mana bar for each mob I kill for negligible experience gain. Root nuking is more efficient. Of course, each nuke breaks the root. Typical battle will be Root, resist, root, nuke, root, resist, root, heal, nuke, nuke, root, heal nuke. I can usually kill two light blue undead this way, or one non-undead before having to sit and med. Again for negligible experience. Solution? Well, upping my plate mitigation is at least a start. I think that raising my melee and defense skills shouldn't be completely out of line either, at least to slightly below the knight classes so as not to step on their toes. And frankly, against undead I should be a killing machine. If more of my AA were tailored to killing undead I would definitely invest the points. Which brings me to my next suggestion.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3. Fix the AA ability Turn Undead - this ability is useless in almost every situation. As has been stated already over and over again, the ability is broken, has always been broken, and should be completely trashed and revamped. It seems to have nice scalability. At its max it does 10K of damage to every undead around you! of course since the damage is attached to a fear component, and every single mob 55+ is immune to fear, all mobs 55+ will resist turn undead. So what is this good for? Well in some lower level zones it can be fun to aggro every green undead mob in a zone and watch TU turn them all into greyish bone powder I guess... But practical use? This ability is worthless in day to day grouping. In my opinion? This should be trashed and every cleric who has invested in it be given their AA back. In its place? An AA like the paladin's slay undead AA, or one similar that ups the damage on our undead nukes and dots. I don't know, but this one is worthless in its current form.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>4. Fix the AA ability Divine Avatar - this is another great idea gone bad. For the AA points this costs it should turn me into a monster for meleeing. Of course with all of our horrid melee skill caps it means that instead of hitting for like 50 max when I hit, I hit for 52 max. Great, instead of 50, miss, miss, miss, 50, miss, 50, miss, miss, miss. I hit for 52, miss, miss, miss, 52, miss, miss, 52, miss. Again, this should be a passive skill that increases our melee damage or skills. Restrict it to undead if you must, I don't care. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>5. Utility Spells - This is my last real suggestion, and the one I care least about. I get by without invisibility. I spend a lot of platinum on invis potions, and I spent an afternoon camping the pegasus in SK to get a levitation cloak. Effectively screwing some mage or whatnot out of their epic item but granting me a much needed spell. Would I turn it down if offered? No, not at all. But I got by for 65 levels without these spells, and I could get by for another 200 AA just fine without them as well. Would it be nice? No question. But if I'm going to have my main role and only real forte given to shaman and druids I would expect more then a little useful utility in exchange.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Are there other areas I think that could be used to balance the priest classes a little bit? yes. Some of them we have seen implemented. Spell casting haste, and the damage mitigation spells are interesting and I think they should scale up from lower levels where they are weaker then they are currently, to the current levels where they are stronger. I've seen lots of people talk about "curses." Do I think clerics should be given a line of "curse" spells? Well it would certainly be an area of specialization that could be unique to clerics. I wouldn't be against it, but it would really be a class changing line of spells. Cursing the mob's attack rating or strength or speed, or spell casting ability would be cool and fun, but not the reason I started a cleric.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The trend in cleric balancing has been fleshing us out as a "battle cleric" and I think that is really the direction we should be going especially versus undead. Pound per pound a cleric or a paladin should be able to make the undead of Norrath quake in their bones. Solo should be at least a slow but effective option for us. Druids and shaman should probably be able to step up to the healer plate in the end game, even with rezzes in a pinch. Clerics probably shouldn't be the forced money sinks throughout most of the game. There are at least two completely useless cleric AA that should be completely revamped. Clerics should remain the kings and queens of healing, but I don't think that most of us would be averse to increases in the druid and shaman healing as long as we are thrown at least a few bones along the way. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Most of us who play clerics as our mains are pretty nice folks. We are forced to group and are therefore pretty sociable. As a rule, we will go out of our way to rez someone in need. Cleric burn out takes its toll. More and more of us are becoming bots as we have no real soloing options for when we can't find groups. This leads to a vicious circle of there not being enough clerics at the end game, increased cleric bots, and druids and shaman wanting more healing power so that raids aren't delayed by the stranglehold that they perceive clerics as having on raid healing.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Well enough of my drunken ramblings. See you all in game soon I hope.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Vyk, Level 65 Cleric</DIV>
<DIV>Drunken Dorf</DIV>
<DIV>Torvonnilous</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
