			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=28168'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=325#M325">7</a> of 11
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 275 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Good Post Andina</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Like I said, I don't think any of my ideas were truly original, and I agree that the difficulty is going to be riding that line between upgrades and not stepping on the paladin's toes. I have been playing this game long enough and a cleric in particular to see almost every other class get awsome upgrades and abilities and for my own class to have been promised the same and only have received a summoned hammer. Basically I'm just pessimistic enough to think that shaman and druids are going to get their healing upgrades. They squeak the loudest and we clerics just sort of sit back and take it.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>As for the CH having broken the game? I don't buy this argument. This is what the druids and shamans always haul out in desperation. "The reason you don't get any real utility spells is that you get CH. Give up your CH and then you can have utility spells." The fact of the matter is that is complete BS. There are whole encounters now where CH simply is not an option. I have gone on whole raids in VT where the only CH I cast is in a 15-20 minute chain during a named mob. If I could share CH with shaman and druids and be promised that they would have to do all the CH chains in every end boss from here on out I would gladly give it up. The thing about CH rotations is, if the raid succeeds everyone always says what a great job the MT did keeping aggro! If you wipe everyone yells at the cleric chain for being sloppy. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I'm pretty sure that druids and shaman are going to get some sort of serious healing upgrade that is going to be a pretty serious incursion on our territory. That being said, I want to make sure that we get something more then a token in return. It isn't that I don't have faith in Sony, I just notice that, as a general rule, we don't cry very loud or whine about the problems in our class. Check out the monk and shadowknight boards for example. There are two classes that Sony is actually listening to (arguably they listened to SK about the problem and then promptly put their concerns on /ignore) but something is going to be done. Likewise for the shaman and druids.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>One serious area for improvement that hasn't been discussed for clerics yet in any thread is itemization. I'm tempted to start a new thread on exaclty this point. But a couple quick examples would be the fact that our elemental BP and Arms both have the exact same focus effect (25% healing on the arms, 30% on the BP I think). That is pretty ridiculous. They are both still nice items and I wouldn't turn it down. But why not give us something different or useful? Why do the shaman ornate BP get their best haste, enchanters get tranquility on one of their items and we get Blessing of Reverence? 25% spell haste is ok I guess. But why do we get our stupid hammer pet a level 53/4 spell on our legs? Why not Virtue? Or even symbol?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Itemization aside, any increase in the healing powers of shaman or druids is going to result in less group desireability for our class. Yes we bring the almight rez to the group, but so do paladins, and I have counted at least two threads on various boards so far clamoring to give all the priest classes, but especially the shaman rezzes to some extent. I saw one thread that demanded shaman being given a rez spell that was cast on the INDIVIDUAL and would either send the person to their corpse with a rez, or would alternatively summon the corpse to the individual along with the rez across the zones. I fully expect to see the other priest classes getting a rez to some extent in an update coming soon. Again, the squeaky wheel and all that. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Soloability? I've been forced to group for experience since level 10 or so. Solo has simply never been an option. Generally when I log in it is because I want some sort of social interaction while I play the game. I actually enjoy groups. Occasionally I am not in a social mood though. Or all the invitations I get are to groups of level 57s who want me for their mistmoor LDON group. Sometimes I just want to be able to go to a zone somplace and pound out an AA or two without having to deal with group politics. I really think that should be at least an option. I'm by no means some outcast misanthrope necromancer or enchanter who is going to spend 12 hours at a time in Valor or Tactics soloing for 20 AA. Likewise, when my group breaks up with 1 yellow left in my AA until some skill I want, I don't think I should have to spend another hour or so looking for a group and getting set up in order to finish it. There should be an option for me to spend that time soloing some place. Lets face it folks, it takes time to find a group, get set up and running efficiently, and once you are going it is poor form to get your last yellow or blue and then promptly log. I consider a group commitment to be about an hour at the minimum unless something comes up.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>peridots - I agree. Like I said, I am personally in a position where it isn't that big a deal any more. I'm in a guild that supplies all the dots for raiding I would ever need, and the stack or two I use in groups doesn't bother me any more. Maybe I've just been beaten into submission. I know there are other classes that have costs as well. Necro pets take a dot at the high end, I think that most of the good spell shields also cost a dot. But clerics have always had the most platinum intensive spells. I remember a time where even the jaspers that our symbols cost me were more then I could easily afford. So yes, I do still feel for the rest of the clerics. Why do our best spells always cost 2-4 peridots, and every other classes spells are component free? I mean Enchanter KEI is arguably the most sought after spell in the game. Its a group spell, just like Aego and Virtue. Their cost? 1000 mana and no component. Cleric Virtue or Aego? 2000-2500 mana and 2-4 peridots. Druids 9? Well, I don't know how much mana it costs and I'm not looking it up. But I bet it doesn't cost 2500 mana and I know it doesn't cost a peridot. It has always seemed to me that sony has sort of had it in for me. Maybe I'm just paranoid...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Cleric Melee and skill versus undead - yeah, I'm not sure this is really the way to go either. I'm just trying to find a niche where they can improve our skills that seems to be at least partially in line with what their "vision" for our class has been in the past. I don't really know how they can do this without stepping on paladin toes at least a little. Keep in mind that if most of these skills were melee linked then we would never be able to match the paladin DPS versus undead if we were also the main healer in the group. Time spent healing the groupmates would be time that we weren't unleashing hell against the undead. I think it would be easiest to make the skills approach those of the knights but always fall a little short. It is just my opinion of course, but I think we should be the "melee" class of the priests. As stated before, that seems to be what the developers had in mind for our class already when they started out with Yaulp and the hammers. Why not give us some more scaleability in this area at the very least?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Curses - Yeah, I agree with you completely on this point. I didn't sign up as a cleric to be the raid debuffer. But unless the developers expand the number of spells that are allowed to be cast on an individual all these brand new and useful spells we are receiving are going to mean precisely zilch. At the moment we are limited to 15. 14 if I am going to be casting a heal over time spell of any kind. Those 14-15 slots fill up QUICK in raids. At the moment it becomes&nbsp;a toss up which spells I decide to keep. I already have a spell casting haste item focus, so I more often then not will click off my BoR in favor of raising my HP or some other form of mana regen spell. If we are limited on buffs, then there is always the other option of casting debuffs on the mob to consider. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Cleric Bots - in reply to one of the above replies. No this isn't a huge issue in groups. I have had it occur several times. I sat there and watched seven toons duke it out in Earth. The cleric was a bot. Just sat there on a horse, and cast one heal per fight. Meanwhile, the group had invited a rogue for DPS for the 6th slot. And why not? The healing requirements for the group were already all taken care of by a bot that didn't need any exp. And there are a LOT of cleric bots out there. Almost every high end guild has a whole cadre of cleric bots they can pull out for raids. Its just as easy to pull one out for a group. Not a huge problem, but one I see growing. And what happens when it does? Its not like I can go solo you know...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Ok. enough rehashing. See you all later...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The Vykster</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
